"Vianna M.L., Cabral A.P., Gherard D.F.","Tm-landsat imagery applied to the study of the impact of global climate change on a tropical coastal environment during the last deglaciation",1993,"International Journal of Remote Sensing","14","16",,"2971","2983",,,10.1080/01431169308904413,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0027790253&partnerID=40&md5=6ca1265fa79c405c4e0a3a54b97f6abf","Instituto Nacional de Pesquisas Espaciais, Divisao de Ciencias da Terra, C.P. 515, Sao Jose dos Campos, SP, 12201-970, Brazil; Royal Holloway University of London, Geology Department, Egham Hill, Egham Surrey, TW20 OEX, United Kingdom","Vianna, M.L., Instituto Nacional de Pesquisas Espaciais, Divisao de Ciencias da Terra, C.P. 515, Sao Jose dos Campos, SP, 12201-970, Brazil; Cabral, A.P., Instituto Nacional de Pesquisas Espaciais, Divisao de Ciencias da Terra, C.P. 515, Sao Jose dos Campos, SP, 12201-970, Brazil; Gherard, D.F., Instituto Nacional de Pesquisas Espaciais, Divisao de Ciencias da Terra, C.P. 515, Sao Jose dos Campos, SP, 12201-970, Brazil, Royal Holloway University of London, Geology Department, Egham Hill, Egham Surrey, TW20 OEX, United Kingdom","The discovery and subsequent mapping of an ancient shoreline at 25 m depth in N-E Brazil by TM-Landsat imagery is described. The study area is located on a technically stable part of the Brazilian shelf which presently shows a minor uplift rate of 0-2 mm year-1, to the north of Natal in the State of Rio Grande do Norte. This submerged shoreline is characterized by the occurrcncc of a large number of long beachrock outcrops (>3km in length), observed by diving, which are comparable to their analogues seen on the present-day beaches of the adjacent coast. The good state of preservation of this shoreline and the large number of carbonate rock ‘reefs’ on it suggest abruptness of a return to transgressive sea-level trend with high growth rates subsequent to a tong-livcd sea-level relating to the 11000-9000 yr b.p. band. By reviewing high resolution paleoclimatic data from this period, we conjecturc that this stillstand could be a consequence of the Younger Dryas cold event in the north Atlantic, which might have also had importance as a driving morphogenetic process for coasts in a global scale. © 1993 Taylor and Francis Ltd.",,"Coastal engineering; Geomorphology; Remote sensing; Sea level; Carbonate rock reefs; Deglaciation; Radiometric dating; TM Landsat imagery; Younger Dryas cold event; Climatology; beachrock; climate change; coastal environment; Landsat TM; Landsat TM imagery; Landsat-TM; satellite sensing; sea level; submerged shoreline; tropical region; Younger Dryas; Atlantic, Brazilian Shelf; Brazil, Rio Grande do Norte, Natal",,,,,,"Aubrey, D.G., Emery, K.O., Uchupi, E., Changing coastal levels of the South America and the Caribbean region from tide-gauge records (1988) Tectonophysics, 154, pp. 269-284; Asmus, H.E., Geologia da Margem Continental Brasileira (1984) Geologia Do Brasil, pp. 443-472. , edited C. Schobbenhaus, D. A. Campos, G. D. Derze, H. E. Asmus (Brasilia: DNPM); Bard, E., Hamelin, B., Fairbanks, R.G., Zindler, A., Calibration of the I4C timescale over the past 30000 years using mass spectrometer U-Th ages from Barbados corals (1990) Nature, 345, pp. 405-410; Bertani, R.T., Costa, I.G., Matos, R.M.D., Evolução tectono-sedimentar, estilo estrulural e habitat do petróleo na Bacia Potiguar (1990) Origem E evoiução De Bacias Sedimentares, pp. 291-309. , edited G. P. De Raja Gabaglia, E. J. Milani (Rio de Janeiro: Petrobrás; Branner, J.C., The stone reefs of Brazil. Their geological and geographical relations, with a chapter on the coral reefs (1904) Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative Zoology, 44, pp. 207-275; Burrows, C.J., A chronology for cool-climate episodes in the Southern Hemisphere 12000-1000 yr b.p (1989) Paleogeography, Paleoctimatologv, Paleoecology, 27, pp. 287-347; Cabral, A.P., Mantovani, J.E., Costa, M.P.F., Lima, R.A.F., Redução do 'striping’ de